Okay, perfect. So let me give you some background. When we first started
working with furniture dealers, we did it very similar to how it\'s
being done in Microsoft D365. Right now. We had our BOM or SIF Import
tool brought in the SIF file. We looked in the catalog. Does that part
number exist? If it does, bring it onto the sales order or the quote. If
it doesn\'t, let\'s go ahead and create it and then bring it onto the
quote. And then all of the detailed information that\'s in the SIF file,
the option code, option description, anything else, bring that into the
transaction. And then we would also create a unique alphanumeric number
called UUID universal ID to make sure that particular item is specific
or unique. Then we\'d also create a lot number.

**\
01:32:07**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
And the lot number is a way for NetSuite to track that to make sure that
it\'s unique. We\'re actually using, and we\'re still using lot numbers.
We\'re really using lot numbers. More like serialized serial number,
except serial numbers go down to the quantity. So like if I ordered part
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and I gave it a lot number, that lot number is, would
represent for all the quantities that you order. So let\'s say you order
a quantity of five. Well, here\'s the lot number for that quantity of
five. A serial number would be, well, here\'s the serial number for
quantity number one. Here\'s a different number for quantity number two.
So it gets very specific. And in furniture you don\'t need to be that
specific.

**\
01:32:48**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
But we do use the lot numbered inventory because we want to make sure
it\'s specific for two primary reasons. I think I call it out on the
slide here. Well, three reasons. Number one, for WIP accounting, we want
to make sure that these items are posting to wip. And I do want to talk
to you about how you guys are doing Wipe and D365 in the moment. And
we\'re also doing it for warehouse traceability. So we want to make sure
that when we receive that product in the warehouse, we know exactly
where it\'s at. And if it didn\'t have a lot number, it wouldn\'t be
unique. So we wouldn\'t know. It would just, you know, it would be the
part number that\'s not unique enough. So lot numbers make it unique so
we can find it on our reports.

**\
01:33:26**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
And then the other big thing is the lot costing versus actual average
costing inventory Management systems typically default to average
costing. We need that particular item because we know it\'s unique with
this set of options to have a very specific cost. And so we\'re using
lot costing to track that and make sure that all the margin reporting is
accurate. Okay, so with that being said, that\'s how we\'re doing it
inside netsuite. Now the other thing, the other major thing that we\'re
doing here is we don\'t go to the part number. Instead of that, we go
one level up where we\'ll say furniture is our item or flooring is our
item. And we might go a little bit more granular than that. We might say
Herman Miller furniture, other furniture.

**\
01:34:10**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
Really the only reason we need a different item is if we need to post a
different GL account. So like if, if for some reason your GL structure
was so flat that you only had one revenue account and one cost of goods
sold account, which I\'m sure you don\'t, but if that was the case, we
would really only need one item because it would post to that, but we
would have all these other things that make that item unique. But as far
as a netsuite item in the item catalog, it the only thing that
differentiates between the items, Sorry, there\'s really two things is
whether it\'s taxable or non taxable and what GL account it\'s posting
to. Now, using that methodology, our item catalog, we probably have 30
or 40 items.

**\
01:34:57**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
As you\'re taking that Herman Miller furniture and you\'re reusing it
hundreds of times on that transaction. And then we have all these other
columns of information that make that particular item unique on the
transaction. So it gives us a lot more flexibility and it keeps the
overall system light because, and because, believe you me, like when
we\'ve implemented other dealers, they have item catalogs of hundreds of
thousands. And you know, when you pull up a list, an item list, you get
that drop down that takes forever to load, you know, and there\'s so
many more to go through. So and the other big thing here with this
methodology or this architecture, I should say of how we\'re doing these
inventory items, lot numbered inventory items is our BOM Import tool. We
can import a file in about 10 seconds.

**\
01:35:49**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
So you can import a thousand lines in 10 seconds. So it makes it
extremely fast for project coordinators to be able to, if I think it\'s
project coordinators in your organization doing the imports. And so with
our previous SIF import tool, because it\'s doing all that Processing it
has to go sit into a process queue. And you might only have a SIF file
that has 10 lines on it, but because it gets stuck in a queue behind
something else that has a thousand lines on it, that thing might be
sitting in there for 20 minutes. You just don\'t know. You might be
waiting forever for that to process. Well, not anymore. With our system,
we can do a thousand lines in about 10 seconds, so it dramatically
increases the speed of it. But I do want you to know it\'s a different
architecture change.

