Do you. Okay, so that sounds similar to how we\'re doing it right now.
So right now. But I, but I will say this is a customization that we
built so natively NetSuite and most systems will do. Revenue is not
associated. Sorry, cost is not associated with invoicing. Revenue is
associated with invoicing and item fulfillment is associated with cost.
So whenever you bring product into your warehouse, you could even pay
that vendor bill that does not have a cost of goods sold impact. It\'s
not until you deliver the product that has a cost of sold impact. So
what we\'ve done is as soon as you generate the customer invoice, then
the item fulfillment transaction that governs cost recognition, that\'s
automatically created in whatever in proportion to the invoice. So if
it\'s a partial invoice, it\'s created in proportion.

**\
01:45:54**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
If you edit the invoice or delete the invoice, the same thing happens to
items fulfillment. They\'re kind of mirrored. So you\'re recognizing
revenue and costs at the. The same time. And we have worked with some
other dealers that want to do it differently. We have one dealer who is
doing it very simply. They\'re. They\'re letting, they\'re letting the
item leave the warehouse drive the cost. And the revenue recognition,
which is I think is a bit more traditional in gap. It\'s probably like
less project accounting, but more gap. Both are gaap. I shouldn\'t say
it that way. It\'s probably less project accounting and more typical in
everything outside of construction.

**\
01:46:36**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
But what happens is the product leaves the warehouse and in that
accounting period, if there is not a corresponding invoice for that
cost, a journal entry is automatically created and the revenue is
accrued and it\'s an automatic reversing journal entry that just
reverses at the beginning of the next month. And so it\'s really the
cost or the product leaving the warehouse that\'s driving the revenue.
So you have that option as well. I actually like that option a little
bit better personally because I think it\'s a little bit cleaner. It\'s,
you know, it\'s revenue is somewhat Divorced from invoicing. It\'s
really driven by when the product leaves your warehouse, which that\'s
technically when custody is changed from you to the client, you\'re
delivering it, installing it. So but something for you to consider. We
built the customizations both. You could do it either way.

**\
01:47:31**\
Marcus Dallacqua\
It\'s really can be configured either way. So we can do it the exact way
that you\'re doing it now, where we\'ve automated that item fulfillment
and that cost recognition or you can let the cost drive the revenue
recognition. The journal entry is automatically created with the
reversal, the reverse in journal entry for accrued revenue.

